content: This is a "lifesaving" app! As Strava is one of the very few open / free API fitness apps, a lot of users do not have the option to upload / sync their activities to other 3rd party apps. This is where SyncMyTracks comes to offer a sufficient solution. I upload my activities to Strava (via my fitness band app options) and from there I use SyncMyTracks to sync the data to Endomondo, MapMyFitness, Garmin Connect, etc, so I can keep up with the corresponding fitness communities. The developer is frequently updating the app to fix any issues that might occur (mind you, though, responsible for those issues is not SyncMyTracks BUT the 3rd party fitness apps developers that sometimes make unannounced changes to their APIs). Keep up the good work !

content: It does what it claims, so is ideal if you fancy a straight switch of trackers, but you may want to do think about what you're doing if you plan to merge several different accounts. As it insists on performing a full sync of all data, between all known accounts, the minute you add any new account details, and as each sync can take a couple of hours and you can't add any further accounts while it's syncing, it could take a day if you wanted to merge the data from 6 trackers you've played with over a couple of years, into say Endomondo. So probably safest to merge two accounts, delete one of them and repeat.  There are a few cosmetic issues with ENGLISH labels being truncated, as I guess the placeholders were sized for the original Spanish, eg. "Activity: Accoun Caus:" on the sync error page.  There are also a few mapping errors, so a general gym workout in mapMyFitness ends up being classified as weight training in Endomondo.  It also doesn't directly support Google's own fitness App's: Tracks and Google Fit, or any of the Fitbit or Withings apps.  Other than that it's about the easiest way to get the details of several hundred workouts into one place.
